e":"Averill","meanings":["English:","apparently from the name of the month (April), Middle English <i>averil</i>, Old French <i>avrill</i>, Latin <i>aprīlis</i>, perhaps with reference to freshness of temperament, or youth, or possibly to the changeable weather of the month.","perhaps occasionally a habitational name from Haverhill in Suffolk, with loss of initial <i>H-</i>. The placename derives from either Old English <i>hæfera</i> ‘oats’ or <i>hæfer</i> ‘he-goat’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Avery  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Molton","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from any of the numerous places so called from Old English <i>mōrtūn</i> ‘settlement by or on a moor’. It is also widely used as a Jewish name, having been adopted as an approximate English equivalent of   Moses ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Molton Avenell was born about 1360, in South Molton, Devon, England, his father, Robert Moulton, was 22 and his mother, Joan De Skinton, was 26. He married Elizabeth de Blackpool about 1380, in South Molton, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1384, in Blackpool, Lancashire, England, at the age of 25."},"et":{"about 1360–1384":"umbes 1360–1384","1360–1384":"1360–1384","1365–1388":"1365–1388","1384–1460":"1384–1460","1339–1396":"1339–1396","1335–1429":"1335–1429","about 1360":"umbes 1360","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1396":"1396","1384":"1384","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1335":"1335","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1429":"1429","about 1384":"umbes 1384","1339":"1339","Blackpool, Lancashire, England":"Blackpool, Lancashire, England","North Molten, Devonshire, England":"North Molton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","South Molton, Devon, England":"South Molton, Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1360–1384":"noin 1360–1384","1360–1384":"1360–1384","1365–1388":"1365–1388","1384–1460":"1384–1460","1339–1396":"1339–1396","1335–1429":"1335–1429","about 1360":"noin 1360","about 1380":"noin 1380","1396":"1396","1384":"1384","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1335":"1335","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1429":"1429","about 1384":"noin 1384","1339":"1339","Blackpool, Lancashire, England":"Blackpool, Lancashire, England","North Molten, Devonshire, England":"North Molton, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","South Molton, Devon, England":"South Molton, Devon, England"},"fr":{"about 1360–138